data.title: heads of state
data.text:
years image name(s), birth- and death data and political party title and reign

The discovery of Canada or actually reaching Newfoundland off the Canadian coast began with the three voyages of John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto) in 1496, 1497 and 1498, after which he was never heard from again. The colonization of Canada, then called New France, started when the Frenchman Jacques Cartier went in search of a western passage to wealthy Asia. He undertook three journeys and was the first governor of the area during this period (1534-1541). French King Francis I appointed Canada's first lieutenant general in 1541; Roberval. From 1611, the territory was ruled by viceroys who did not reside in Canada. From 1627 the viceroy was replaced by a governor and from 1636 a Governor-General: 1496-1498 Giovanni Caboto, also: John Cabot, born about 1450 in Gaeta of Castiglione Chiavarese, Italy and missing since 1498 on the Atlantic Ocean, about 38 years old. Explorer, undertook three journeys to what would later become Canada:
